Pour the boiling @water{300%ml} into a large #saucepan{} along with half the
@chicken stock powder{1%stock pot} and stir to dissolve.

Stir in the @couscous{150%g}, remove from the heat and cover with a #lid{}.

Leave to the side until ready to serve.

== Lamb ==

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a #frying pan{} on high heat.

When really hot, add the @lamb strips{240%g}, season with @salt and @pepper and
stir fry until browned all over, ~{1-2%minutes}, then remove to a #bowl{} and
set aside.

> TIP: Don't overcook the lamb here, you are just browning it. We will finish
> cooking it later!

Halve, peel and finely slice the @red onion{1}(peeled and finely sliced). Return
the frying pan to medium heat (add a splash of @oil if it's dry) and add the
onion. Cook, stirring occasionally, until soft, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Meanwhile, quarter the @courgette{1} lengthways and chop widthways into small
chunks. Roughly chop the @dried apricots{40%g}.

Drain and rinse the @chickpeas{1%400g can} in a #sieve{}.

== Tagine ==

Add the @tagine paste{1} and apricots to the #frying pan{} and stir. Cook for
~{1%minute}, then add the courgette.

Pour in the @chopped tomatoes{1%12oz can}, remaining @chicken stock powder{1/2%stock pot}
and the chickpeas. Bring to the boil then reduce the heat to medium and simmer
until thick and tomatoey, ~{5-6%minutes}.

Return the lamb (and any juices that have come out) to the tagine and cook,
stirring occasionally, for another ~{2-3%minutes}.

Season to taste with @salt and @pepper if needed.

Fluff the couscous up with a #fork{}.

Spoon the couscous into #bowls{} and top with the lamb tagine. Scatter over some
@flaked almonds{25%g} to finish. Enjoy!